sec.p:
As a proof-of-concept demonstration, the method was applied to the determination of Cu2+ in spiked water samples at concentrations below the WHO and EPA limits for drinking water. Due to the dissolution of MCC, PVP and Mg-stearate from the tablet during extraction and the complexity of some natural waters, matrix effects were calculated using the formulae: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:\mathrm{M}\mathrm{E}\left(\mathrm{\%}\right)=\left(1-\frac{{\mathrm{S}}_{\mathrm{D}\mathrm{W}}}{{\mathrm{S}}_{\mathrm{s}\mathrm{a}\mathrm{m}\mathrm{p}\mathrm{l}\mathrm{e}}}\right)\times\:100\left(\raisebox{1ex}{$0$}\!\left/\:\!\raisebox{-1ex}{$0$}\right.\right)$$\end{document} where SDW is the net signal (absorbance of the sample minus the absorbance blank) of the target metal ion in distilled water, and Ssample is the net signal of the target metal ion in the sample matrix. Matrix effects were weak (< 10%) in all freshwater samples (Table 4) and moderate in seawater (~ 34%) (results not shown). These matrix effects may be related to (a) the large excess of chloride anions which may strongly compete gluconate for the complexation of Cu2+, (b) the large excess of Ca2+ and Mg2+ that may effectively be complexed by gluconate, and (c) the compression of the electrical double-layer of the MNPs which is involved in extraction. Therefore, spiking experiments to assess the method’s accuracy were performed in freshwater samples.
